I’m still struggling, I still have bad days, but I’m doing a lot better. I don’t feel as sick when I eat, I don’t get as light headed, and I can play games like Just Dance again. It’s taken me about a year to get to a point where I felt like I could talk about this.

This last year has been one of the hardest for me, food has been my enemy, exercise has been a savior and a punishment.

It wasn’t until May that I decided to reclaim myself, reclaim food, and reclaim letting myself live and be happy.

A then-regular told me, on stream, “I don’t know why you’re telling us this, your body looks fine; you shouldn’t worry about it.”

This was a statement that was intended to be uplifting, but it made me second-guess myself and my disorder, leading to a full blown relapse.

I’ve been in a constant recovery/relapse cycle with anorexia since my senior year of high school, and last summer I was on the verge of a relapse and seeing myself on camera was the almost tipping point, so I spoke about it to bring awareness and to be transparent.

Last summer for a follow milestone, I streamed Just Dance on my Twitch. While I was dancing, I caught a glimpse of myself on the camera and stopped mid-song and had a small cry session and heart-to-heart with my viewers about what was going on.

⚠️ cw: eating disorder and body image talk

It’s been over a year since I last streamed Just Dance, and over a year since I allowed myself to have fun with it.
